## What's inside

__FEATURE_LINKS__

## Setup

```bash
python -m venv .venv
. .venv/bin/activate        # Windows: .venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -e ".[dev]"
```

Copy the example environment file and edit it — in particular, set an honest
`USER_AGENT` with a real contact:

```bash
cp .env.example .env
```

## Run

```bash
# Runs the example spider against START_URLS and writes output/results.jsonl
python -m __PACKAGE_NAME__
```

Everything is configurable via environment variables (see `.env.example`), e.g.:

```bash
START_URLS="https://example.com/,https://example.org/" REQUESTS_PER_SECOND=0.5 python -m __PACKAGE_NAME__
```

## Where to change things

| File | Responsibility |
| ---- | -------------- |
| `src/__PACKAGE_NAME__/settings.py` | All tunables (rate, timeout, cache, robots, proxy). |
| `src/__PACKAGE_NAME__/fetcher.py` | The polite fetch layer (session, rate limit, retries, cache, robots). |
| `src/__PACKAGE_NAME__/parse.py` | Turn HTML into rows — **edit the selectors here**. |
| `src/__PACKAGE_NAME__/spider.py` | The crawl loop and entrypoint. |
| `src/__PACKAGE_NAME__/export.py` | CSV / JSONL writers. |

## Testing

```bash
pytest
```

The included smoke tests are offline and deterministic.

